      {
        "id": 10083,
        "name": "",
        "username": "agyaani",
        "avatar_template": "https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/a/9fc29f/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2021-10-07T11:27:57.801Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Appreciate your reply <a class=\"mention\" href=\"/u/krzysfr\">@KrzysFR</a> . I think what you\u2019re describing is a different solution though. Here, I meant \u2018actors\u2019 in a very restrictive sense, the way it is meant in the FDB/Flow paper \u2013 just synctatic sugar to get rid of nested callbacks.</p>\n<p>For kicks OR as a mental exercise OR as a useful pattern for testing:<br>\nTo deterministically simulate a service written in C# (say) on a single thread, we\u2019d need alternatives for a bunch of language constructs like</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Those from the System.Threading.* family like Tasks, TaskScheduler</li>\n<li>Current time, CPU/disk utilization,</li>\n<li>Random seeds</li>\n<li>Async/Await</li>\n<li>Non-blocking IO</li>\n<li>\u2026<br>\nOf these, I am curious how the Async/Await pattern would be handled.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Thanks for your patience!</p>",
